story:
Brighter and Better than Ever!! 

The residents of Strath Close and neighbouring roads have always loved to light up our homes for Christmas. After such a difficult year for many we have decided to really raise some Christmas Cheer in 2020. As well as decs to do Vegas proud we have a 12ft Christmas tree for all to enjoy at the top of the Close. 

And we hope that we can encourage those who visit to make a donation to Macmillan Cancer Support! No matter how small (or large), your support will be very much appreciated.

Thank You and Merry Christmas!! 🌲

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
I think most families have their stories of someone who has had cancer. The news that a family member or friend has cancer may well be amongst the most devastating things you hear in your life. It's natural that you, as well as the person diagnosed, will need empathy, support and information. Macmillan provide that, and so much more.

Christmas was always a special time for my aunt, who loved decorations, presents, and everything else festive. After we lost my aunt to cancer, I want to thank the kind people at Macmillan for their support to my aunt and my family during an incredibly difficult time; Christmas seemed like the natural time to do that.

100% of your donation goes to Macmillan Cancer Support, to allow them to continue their amazing work. Thank you.

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising!

This year, I was supposed to run the Edinburgh Marathon but it was sadly cancelled due to COVID so I am excited to be taking part in the challenge virtually....I will completing the marathon over 2 days on 11th and 12th December.

Macmillan Cancer Support is a charity very close to my heart this year. I know that Macmillan do an amazing job helping everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. 

Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

Your support would mean a great deal to me and your donations will make a real difference to those living with cancer.

Cassie

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. As you may know, I sadly lost my uncle this July to a heart attack. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from the public that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thank you so much x

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Help us raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas! 

During December hundreds of our fundraising dogs across the UK would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at supermarket and street collections, Christmas fairs and festive coffee mornings. Our four-legged fundraisers support the 400+ fundraising groups across the UK from Glasgow to Plymouth and everywhere in between.

Due to the current situation, most of our fundraising groups will not be out collecting this festive season, and our four-legged fundraisers will be very much missed! We hope you will do your bit and help us as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! Heres how you can join in: 

	Donate £12 and share our posts across social media nominating a friend, family member or colleague to  get involved

	Set up your own fundraiser on this page

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Throughout December, I'm streaming daily for 5 charities, including this one, as part of Stocky's December Donation Drive 2020.

Every day, young lives hang in the balance as patients, families and staff battle the most complex illnesses. Every day, the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs that change the lives of thousands of children – and change the world.

Despite the greatest challenges a child can face, the hospital is a place where being sick does not always mean being sad. And it’s a place where you’ll find – today and every day – some of the bravest people you could ever meet.

This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support, and every day is a chance for you to make a difference.

story:
On the 8th of November my family and I suffered the loss of someone we loved. My grandad Alan unfortunately passed away after a tough battle with Cancer. So I have decided, that in his memory, I am going to take on the challenge of running a minimum of 5km every day for 30 days starting on the 1st of December. I have decided to raise money to go towards Cancer Research UK.  My wife Ginny has decided to support me and join in the challenge too so she will also be walking/running 5km every day. On Saturdays and Sundays and then a few days during the holidays we will have a special guest running alongside us as my nearly 8 year old son Seb has decided he would also like to join in and run to help raise money.

eventName: New York in time for Christmas
story:
We have been left feeling nothing short of devastated to receive the news of my dad's cancer diagnosis. Everything has happened so quickly and I feel like I have to do something. Telling the children was the hardest thing I've ever done and Gratz and I figured getting them involved in a challenge would help keep them focused, energised and fit at the same time.

We chose New York as that is where my brother and family live. My mum and dad were supposed to visit at Easter but couldn't due to Covid.

This is a TOUGH challenge as it equates to 30+ km per day but we are determined to smash it! 

We would be so grateful for any donations to this amazing charity.


Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
Fitness fundraiser

Thanks for taking the time to visit my Justgiving page.

I am doing this challenge, which I hope a few of you will join in with, as my brother was diagnosed with oesphageal cancer earlier this year and it has been a really tough time for us all as a family, but especially for him. We are so thankful that through the great work of Cancer Research UK new treatments were available to him that meant his condition was treatable. I am glad to say that his recent operation was a success and he just has one more round of chemo to go.

I appreciate that this has been a challenging year for all of us, both emotionally and financially, but any amount you are able to donate, no matter how small will be greatly appreciated.

My challenge is taking place on Zoom on Tuesday 29th December and I am aiming to teach 12 thirty minute exercise classes on the hour every hour from 8am - 8pm.  I would love it if some of you took part too or just popped on to add support!  I'm going to need it!  I will send out the class timetable and Zoom link nearer the time and hope to see some of you there!

Many thanks,

Joolz x

story:
Hi! My Dad and I are climbing Mount Kilimanjaro at the end of January for Cancer Research UK. Nearly everyone you meet has known someone affected by this disease, so I thought by (hopefully!!) completing one of my dreams, I could also do something good along the way. 

On the 24th of January (COVID allowing), we're flying to Tanzania and starting our 8-day trek to the summit via the Lemosho route! 

All money is going directly to Cancer Research UK.

story:
Thank you for supporting our Christmas campaign in Liverpool. Marie Curie helps over 1,000 local people and their families every year providing the very best specialist care for people at the very end of their lives. Our hospice is warm, welcoming and friendly and we not only look after those directly in our care but their loved ones as well. 
The Coronavirus pandemic has led to a devastating loss of income as many  fundraising activities have been cancelled. 
Our target is to raise £20,000 to pay for care for Christmas Eve, Christmas Day and Boxing Day.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story: Our lovely Nick sadly lost his brave fight against his prolonged illness on the evening of 25 November.  Nick loved spending time on the water with his family and friends during his wonderful family holidays in Salcombe, Devon.  Nick held in high esteem the work that the RNLI do to keep our waters and beaches safe  - RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising.  This charity was close to Nick's heart and he was great supporter.  Nick's family have nominated this charity for donations in loving memory of our dear friend and colleague.

story:

Over December, I will be doing 1000 burpees, rowing 10km and running 5km. I am also doing various minecraft videos on what you can do to help. You can check them out at https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC84r2Ij5dT8-_2FDOdlDN7A.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: A child dies every two minutes from malaria. We are one of the world’s leading non profit organisations specialising in protecting the most vulnerable from the burden of malaria and other communicable diseases. To know more about how we spend your money and where we work, please visit our website.
charity.name: Malaria Consortium
story:
Ally spent her life caring for others - her large family, and even larger adopted family, her neighbors, and everyone else who came across her path (in fact David is fond of telling a story about the time Ally invited her ex-husband's cousin's ex-girlfriend to Christmas because she didn't have plans). We (David and Joel), want to continue this tradition of extending love and support to others. We're asking that you help us by supporting a charity whose mission was so dear to Ally's heart.

We've chosen 5,000 pounds as our target because this is the estimated cost of saving a single life from Give Well. Thank you for any amount you can donate in support of this mission. If you can, please share your favorite story of our Mum in the comments - we would love to read them all.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Ordinary people are bearing the brunt of an increasingly brutal conflict in Yemen.

After five years of war, more than 80 percent of the population, 24 million people, need humanitarian assistance.

MSFs activities in Yemen are among their most extensive worldwide, but the needs remain huge while the healthcare system is even weaker than it was in 2015, when conflict erupted.

MSF is running the only COVID-19 treatment centre for the whole of southern Yemen. Their teams are working around the clock to provide the best level of care that they can.

How your support makes an impact

£10 could provide eight dressings for wounds 
£17 could provide two leg splints to treat fractures 
£31 could pay for 40 oxygen masks 
£97 could pay for a physiotherapist for one day 

Thank you so much.
title: Support MSF's medical teams to treat patients in Yemen.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
